[1]
Date: Wed 13 Aug 2003
From: Dr Tom Brown <tbrown@uga.edu>

Additional comment on (avian) retroviral neoplasms
--------------------------------------------------
Dr Brad Chadwick's description of facial tumors in Tasmanian devils [see:
Undiagnosed deaths, Tasmanian devils - Australia (02) 20030812.1999] is
interesting, and apparently tragic for this signature Tasmanian species.
I suggest one small potential addition to his notes on site of exposure
induced retroviral neoplasms in avian species. As he described, avian type
C retroviruses induce tumors in immunologically tolerant viremic chickens
that are most often multisystemic lymphosarcomas for subgroups A and B, and
myelocytomas for subgroup J (ALV-J). However, a minor percentage of
chickens exposed horizontally by inhalation as neonates, and which become
tolerant/viremic to ALV-J leukosis viruses, develop subepithelial mucosal
laryngeal and tracheal myelocytomas as their initial tumor. There is then
subsequent multisystemic and leukemic progression. These initial
tracheal/laryngeal tumors have not been definitively proven to be due to
local exposure to virus-laden fomites, and there are alternate
explanations. However, in this subset of ALV-J infected chickens,
horizontal exposure and first tumor do occur at this same site.
--
Dr Tom P Brown, DVM, MS, PhD
Professor, Departments of Avian Medicine and Veterinary Pathology
College of Veterinary Medicine
University of Georgia
<tbrown@uga.edu>
